Explanation:

I inspected the TableOpsResources.create method and the CreateTableRequest model to determine the JSON body expected by POST /api/v0/ops/tables/create.

- The endpoint consumes application/json and the method signature is create(CreateTableRequest request). So this endpoint expects a single body parameter.
- CreateTableRequest fields (from src/main/java/.../CreateTableRequest.java):
  - keyspace_name (String) — required. validate() enforces non-empty.
  - table_name (String) — required. validate() enforces non-empty.
  - columns (List<Column>) — required. validate() enforces non-empty.
  - options (Map<String, Object>) — optional. The code allows values that are either String or Map<String,String>. Swagger 2.0 cannot express a union cleanly; I represent options as an object with additionalProperties (any) and added a description explaining allowed shapes.
- Column (inner class) fields:
  - name (String) — required.
  - type (String) — required.
  - kind (enum) — values PARTITION_KEY, CLUSTERING_COLUMN, REGULAR, STATIC (default REGULAR).
  - position (int) — optional (used for key/clustering columns).
  - order (ClusteringOrder) — optional; in Cassandra this is typically ASC/DESC, so I used enum values "ASC" and "DESC".
- The request.validate() logic implies that keyspace_name, table_name, and columns are required, and column.name and column.type are required. Other inter-field constraints (e.g., clustering order required when kind is CLUSTERING_COLUMN) cannot be expressed in a simple parameter schema and are therefore not encoded as required in the schema.

Based on this, the POST /api/v0/ops/tables/create parameters array contains a single body parameter with an inline schema describing the CreateTableRequest structure and Column items.

